ce:section.ce:para:
The modified electrode was used to detect HIS in human serum and fish tuna samples (Tables 2 and 3

                        ). In these experiments, 100 µL of human serum and tuna fish extract were treated with 6.0 mL phosphate buffer (pH 7.0), and the analysis was conducted before and after spiking with different concentrations of HIS solutions. The recoveries % and RSDs % in human serum and tunas fish were found 98.5–102.5% (RSDs %= 1.8–3.6%) and 97.2–102.1% (RSDs = 2.5–3.8%), respectively. These data confirm the high selectivity and precision of the modified sensor for the detection of HIS in real samples. In addition, the proposed method was compared with the UHPLC–MS/MS method [46] for detection of HIS, and it was found that there is no significant difference between them, suggesting the accuracy of the proposed sensor. It is worth mentioning that the normal levels of HIS in human and canned tuna fish are 0.0–10.8 nM and 50–100 mg Kg−1 
                        [47], respectively.
